Now I see! At lines 2506-2525 in `simplifyOrInst`, there's already code that uses `isImpliedCondition` to simplify `or` of two boolean values. But it only checks the case where `LHSIsTrue` is `false`:

```cpp
if (std::optional<bool> Implied =
        isImpliedCondition(Op0, Op1, Q.DL, false)) {
  // If Op0 is false implies Op1 is false, then Op1 is a subset of Op0.
  if (*Implied == false)
    return Op0;
  // If Op0 is false implies Op1 is true, then at least one is always true.
  if (*Implied == true)
    return ConstantInt::getTrue(Op0->getType());
}
```

But it doesn't check the case where `LHSIsTrue` is `true`! 

If `Op0` is true implies `Op1` is true (i.e., `isImpliedCondition(Op0, Op1, Q.DL, true)` returns `true`), then `Op0` is a subset of `Op1`, and `Op0 | Op1` simplifies to `Op1`.

Similarly, if `Op1` is true implies `Op0` is true, then `Op1 | Op0` simplifies to `Op0`.

Let me verify: if A implies B, then A | B = B (because if A is true, B is also true, so the result is true; if A is false, the result is B). Yes, this is correct.

So the fix should be in `simplifyOrInst` to add the missing `LHSIsTrue = true` case.

Let me also check `simplifyAndInst` for the dual case.

